NECRO LIT NAZI TIME
The phrase is actually "champing at the bit"

Champing is similar to chomping, and the word chomp originally derives from it, but there's subtle differences. Chomping carries more connotation of actually biting on something or through something, for one thing, while champing can mean more of a gnashing or grinding of teeth.

The word is barely used outside of horse behavior these days, but since the idiom is quite specifically referring to that behavior

Champing is still preferred in published works that have (mostly) been past an editor, though it's getting close to 50-50 these days while "chomping" was still more or less at zero until the 1960s. It'd be interesting to see graphs that culled titles likely to be very lightly or barely edited and see how or if this affects the prevalence.

It's definitely changing, since the rarity and unfamiliarity of the word champ means people readily copy the original error, but right now if you had to split with one right and one wrong, chomp is just an extremely common error.

It's also sad to see the flexibility of language diminish with closely related terms clumping into each other.
